Durban - A 44-year-old man, believed to be hiring out firearms to criminals, is due back in court on Monday. The arrest and subsequent court appearance comes after police found a firearms cache at his Isithumba Reserve homestead last week. Acting on intelligence gathered, police pounced on the man’s homestead in Phumekhaya Road, in Inchanga. Colonel Thembeka Mbhele, police spokesperson, said the man was found in possession of a revolver, AK47 rifle and R4 rifle, six rifle magazines with an assortment of 387 rounds of ammunition. “Extensive police investigation revealed that the suspect is renting out the firearms and ammunition to criminals in the province. The firearms will be sent for ballistic testing to ascertain if they were used in the commission of crime in the country as the investigation is continuing,” she said. The man is due back in court on charges of the possession of unlicensed firearms and ammunition. Major General Bheki Langa, KwaZulu-Natal Acting Police Commissioner, praised the members for the arrest and the seizure of unlicensed firearms. Daily News